# Code Patterns & Conventions

## Module Ownership

- All fraction math (pure functions) → `src/engine/`
- TutorBrain interface + implementations → `src/brain/`
- State types, reducer, checkpoint → `src/state/`
- React components → `src/components/`
- Lesson scripts (JSON) → `src/content/`
- Exploration observer → `src/observers/`
- Sound synthesis → `src/audio/`
- E2E tests → `cypress/`

## Coding Standards

- Every function must have TypeScript type annotations (params + return)
- No `any` types — use explicit typing everywhere. Use `unknown` if truly unknown.
- Interfaces over type aliases for object shapes
- All React components are functional (no class components)
- State: `useReducer` only. No `useState` for lesson state. Local UI state (e.g., animation flags) may use `useState`.
- Environment variables via Vite's `import.meta.env`, never hardcoded
- No `console.log` in production code — use a debug flag or remove before commit

## Type Contracts

The shared types in `src/state/types.ts` are the contract between engine and UI:
- `Fraction`, `FractionBlock`, `LessonState`, `LessonAction`, `ChatMessage`
- Do NOT change these interfaces without understanding all consumers
- Freeze `types.ts` after Day 1 — changes require explicit justification

## Naming

- Components: PascalCase (`FractionBlock.tsx`)
- Hooks: camelCase with `use` prefix (`useLessonState`)
- Engine functions: camelCase (`areEquivalent`, `simplify`)
- Action types: SCREAMING_SNAKE_CASE (`SPLIT_BLOCK`, `ADVANCE_SCRIPT`)
- CSS classes: kebab-case (`fraction-block`, `comparison-zone`)
- Test files: colocated with source (`FractionEngine.test.ts` next to `FractionEngine.ts`)
